# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermodynamic-cycles
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The **Brayton cycle**, also known as the **Joule cycle**, is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the operation of certain heat engines that have air or some other gas as their working fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] It is characterized by isentropic compression and expansion, and isobaric heat addition and rejection, though practical engines have adiabatic rather than isentropic steps.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The most common current application is in airbreathing jet engines and gas turbine engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The engine cycle is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer, who developed the Brayton Ready Motor in 1872, using a piston compressor and piston expander.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] An engine using the cycle was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791, using a reciprocating compressor and a turbine expander.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] There are two main types of Brayton cycles: closed and open.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In a closed cycle, the working gas stays inside the engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Heat is introduced with a heat exchanger or external combustion and expelled with a heat exchanger.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] With the open cycle, air from the atmosphere is drawn in, goes through three steps of the cycle, and is expelled again to the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Open cycles allow for internal combustion.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Although the cycle is open, it is conventionally assumed for the purposes of thermodynamic analysis that the exhaust gases are reused in the intake, enabling analysis as a closed cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1872, George Brayton applied for a patent for his "Ready Motor", a reciprocating heat engine operating on a gas power cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The engine was a two-stroke and produced power on every revolution.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Brayton engines used a separate piston compressor and piston expander, with compressed air heated by internal fire as it entered the expander cylinder.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The first versions of the Brayton engine were vapor engines which mixed fuel with air as it entered the compressor; town gas was used or a surface carburetor was also used for mobile operation .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The fuel / air was contained in a reservoir / tank and then it was admitted to the expansion cylinder and burned.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] As the fuel/air mixture entered the expansion cylinder, it was ignited by a pilot flame.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A screen was used to prevent the fire from entering or returning to the reservoir.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In early versions of the engine, this screen sometimes failed and an explosion would occur.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1874, Brayton solved the explosion problem by adding the fuel just prior to the expander cylinder.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The engine now used heavier fuels such as kerosene and fuel oil.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Brayton produced and sold "Ready Motors" to perform a variety of tasks like water pumping, mill operation, running generators, and marine propulsion.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The "Ready Motors" were produced from 1872 to sometime in the 1880s; several hundred such motors were likely produced during this time period.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Brayton licensed the design to Simone in the UK.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Many variations of the layout were used; some were single-acting and some were double-acting.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Some had under walking beams; others had overhead walking beams.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Both horizontal and vertical models were built.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Sizes ranged from less than one to over 40 horsepower.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Critics of the time claimed the engines ran smoothly and had a reasonable efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Brayton-cycle engines were some of the first internal combustion engines used for motive power.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1875, John Holland used a Brayton engine to power the world's first self-propelled submarine (Holland boat #1).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1879, a Brayton engine was used to power a second submarine, the *Fenian Ram*.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] John Philip Holland's submarines are preserved in the Paterson Museum in the Old Great Falls Historic District of Paterson, New Jersey.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Selden patented the first internal combustion automobile.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Inspired by the internal combustion engine invented by Brayton displayed at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876, Selden patented a four-wheel car working on a smaller, lighter, multicylinder version.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] He then filed a series of amendments to his application which stretched out the legal process, resulting in a delay of 16 years before the patent was granted on November 5, 1895.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1903, Selden sued Ford for patent infringement and Henry Ford fought the Selden patent until 1911.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Selden had never actually produced a working car, so during the trial, two machines were constructed according to the patent drawings.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Ford argued his cars used the four-stroke Alphonse Beau de Rochas cycle or Otto cycle and not the Brayton-cycle engine used in the Selden auto.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Ford won the appeal of the original case.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1887, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke direct-injection oil engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The fuel system used a variable-quantity pump and liquid-fuel, high-pressure, spray-type injection.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The liquid was forced through a spring-loaded, relief-type valve (injector) which caused the fuel to become divided into small droplets.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Injection was timed to occur at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A platinum igniter provided the source of ignition.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In this manner, the engine fired on every power stroke and speed and output were controlled solely by the quantity of fuel injected.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 1890, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke, air-blast oil engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The fuel system delivered a variable quantity of vaporized fuel to the center of the cylinder under pressure at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The ignition source was an igniter made from platinum wire.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A variable-quantity injection pump provided the fuel to an injector where it was mixed with air as it entered the cylinder.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A small crank-driven compressor provided the source for air.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] This engine also used the lean-burn system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Rudolf Diesel originally proposed a very high compression, constant-temperature cycle where the heat of compression would exceed the heat of combustion, but after several years of experiments, he realized that the constant-temperature cycle would not work in a piston engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Early Diesel engines use an air blast system which was pioneered by Brayton in 1890.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Consequently, these early engines use the constant-pressure cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A Brayton-type engine consists of three components: a compressor, a mixing chamber, and an expander.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Modern Brayton engines are almost always a turbine type, although Brayton only made piston engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In the original 19th-century Brayton engine, ambient air is drawn into a piston compressor, where it is compressed; ideally an isentropic process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The compressed air then passes through a mixing chamber where fuel is added, an isobaric process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The pressurized air and fuel mixture is then ignited in an expansion cylinder and energy is released, causing the heated air and combustion products to expand through a piston/cylinder, another ideally isentropic process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Some of the work extracted by the piston/cylinder is used to drive the compressor through a crankshaft arrangement.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Gas turbine engines are also Brayton engines, with three components: an air compressor, a combustion chamber, and a gas turbine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] 2. isobaric process – the compressed air then passes through a combustion chamber, where fuel is burned, heating that air—a constant-pressure process, since the chamber is open to flow in and out.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] 3. isentropic process – the heated, pressurized air then gives up its energy, expanding through a turbine (or series of turbines).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Some of the work extracted by the turbine is used to drive the compressor.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] 4. isobaric process – heat rejection (in the atmosphere).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Since neither the compression nor the expansion can be truly isentropic, losses through the compressor and the expander represent sources of inescapable working inefficiencies.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In general, increasing the compression ratio is the most direct way to increase the overall power output of a Brayton system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Figure 1 indicates how the cycle efficiency changes with an increase in pressure ratio.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Figure 2 indicates how the specific power output changes with an increase in the gas turbine inlet temperature for two different pressure ratio values.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The highest gas temperature in the cycle occurs where work transfer to the high pressure turbine (rotor inlet) takes place.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] This is lower than the highest gas temperature in the engine (combustion zone).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The maximum cycle temperature is limited by the turbine materials and required turbine life.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] This also limits the pressure ratios that can be used in the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] For a fixed-turbine inlet temperature, the net work output per cycle increases with the pressure ratio (thus the thermal efficiency) and the net work output.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] With less work output per cycle, a larger mass flow rate (thus a larger system) is needed to maintain the same power output, which may not be economical.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In most common designs, the pressure ratio of a gas turbine ranges from about 11 to 16.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A closed Brayton cycle recirculates the working fluid; the air expelled from the turbine is reintroduced into the compressor, this cycle uses a heat exchanger to heat the working fluid instead of an internal combustion chamber.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The closed Brayton cycle is used, for example, in closed-cycle gas turbines for power generation in space.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] In 2002, a hybrid open solar Brayton cycle was operated for the first time consistently and effectively with relevant papers published, in the frame of the EU SOLGATE program.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The air was heated from 570 to over 1000K into the combustor chamber.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Further hybridization was achieved during the EU Solhyco project running a hybridized Brayton cycle with solar energy and biodiesel only.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] This technology was scaled up to 4.6 MW within the project Solugas located near Seville, where it is currently demonstrated at precommercial scale.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] A Brayton cycle that is driven in reverse uses work to move heat.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] This makes it a form of gas refrigeration cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] When air is the working fluid, it is known as the Bell Coleman cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] It is also used in the LNG industry for subcooling LNG using power from a gas turbine to drive the compressor.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] This is an open Brayton cycle which also generates work from heat, but with a different order of the stages.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] Incoming air is first heated at atmospheric pressure, and then passes through the turbine, generating work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The gas, now at a pressure lower than atmospheric, is cooled in a heat exchanger.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] The compressor raises the pressure again so the gas can be expelled to the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/brayton-cycle] NASA is considering the Brayton cycle for its lunar nuclear reactor to be launched in 2030.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] A **Carnot cycle** is an ideal thermodynamic cycle proposed by French physicist Sadi Carnot in 1824 and expanded upon by others in the 1830s and 1840s.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] By Carnot's theorem, it provides an upper limit on the efficiency of any classical thermodynamic engine during the conversion of heat into work, or conversely, the efficiency of a refrigeration system in creating a temperature difference through the application of work to the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] In a Carnot cycle, a system or engine transfers energy in the form of heat between two thermal reservoirs at temperatures *T*H and *T*C (referred to as the hot and cold reservoirs, respectively), and a part of this transferred energy is converted to the work done by the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The cycle is reversible, merely transferring thermal energy between the thermal reservoirs and the system without gain or loss.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] When work is applied to the system, heat moves from the cold to hot reservoir (heat pump or refrigeration).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] When heat moves from the hot to the cold reservoir, the system applies work to the environment.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The work *W* done by the system or engine to the environment per Carnot cycle depends on the temperatures of the thermal reservoirs per cycle such as *W* = *Q*H(*T*H − *T*C)/*T*H, where *Q*H is heat transferred from the hot reservoir to the system per cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] **(reversible adiabatic) expansion of the gas ( work output).** For this step (2 to 3 on **Figure 1**) the gas in the engine is thermally insulated from both the hot and cold reservoirs, thus they neither gain nor lose heat.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The gas continues to expand with reduction of its pressure, doing work on the surroundings (raising the piston; Stage Two figure, right), and losing an amount of internal energy equal to the work done.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The loss of internal energy causes the gas to cool.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] In this step it is cooled to a temperature that is infinitesimally higher than the cold reservoir temperature *T*C.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The gas temperature is infinitesimally higher than *T*C to allow heat transfer from the gas to the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] There is no change in temperature, it is an isothermal process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The surroundings do work on the gas, pushing the piston down (Stage Three figure, right).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] An amount of energy earned by the gas from this work exactly transfers as a heat energy *Q*C < 0 (negative as leaving from the system, according to the universal convention in thermodynamics) to the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] **Compression.** (4 to 1 on **Figure 1**) Once again the gas in the engine is thermally insulated from the hot and cold reservoirs, and the engine is assumed to be frictionless and the process is slow enough, hence reversible.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] During this step, the surroundings do work on the gas, pushing the piston down further (Stage Four figure, right), increasing its internal energy, compressing it, and causing its temperature to rise back to the temperature infinitesimally less than *T*H due solely to the work added to the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] At this point the gas is in the same state as at the start of step 1.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] This is true as *Q*C and *T*C are both smaller in magnitude and in fact are in the same ratio as *Q*H/*T*H.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] When a Carnot cycle is plotted on a pressure–volume diagram (**Figure 1**), the isothermal stages follow the isotherm lines for the working fluid, the adiabatic stages move between isotherms, and the area bounded by the complete cycle path represents the total work that can be done during one cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] From point 1 to 2 and point 3 to 4 the temperature is constant (isothermal process).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Heat transfer from point 4 to 1 and point 2 to 3 are equal to zero (adiabatic process).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] A Carnot cycle plotted on a Temperature-entropy diagram (**Figure 4**) is rather simple.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Isothermic paths are horizontal, adiabatic paths are vertical.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The area enclosed by the cycle is the amount of heat energy extracted from the hot reservoir but not delivered to the cold reservoir, which has been converted into work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Defining ΔS = *S*B − *S*A, the heat energy injected into the engine is *Q*H = *T*HΔS and the heat energy extracted from the engine is *Q*C = *T*CΔS, which is the portion of the injected energy that is unavailable to do work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The engine is reversibly transporting entropy from the hot reservoir to the cold reservoir.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] This is the Carnot heat engine working efficiency definition as the fraction of the work done by the engine system to the thermal energy received by the system from the hot reservoir per cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] This thermal energy is the cycle initiator.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] A Carnot heat-engine cycle described is a totally reversible cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] That is, all the processes that compose it can be reversed, in which case it becomes the Carnot heat pump and refrigeration cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] This time, the cycle remains exactly the same except that the directions of any heat and work interactions are reversed.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Heat is absorbed from the low-temperature reservoir, heat is rejected to a high-temperature reservoir, and a work input is required to accomplish all this.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The *P*–*V* diagram of the reversed Carnot cycle is the same as for the Carnot heat-engine cycle except that the directions of the processes are reversed.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] It can be seen from the above diagram that for any cycle operating between temperatures *T*H and *T*C, none can exceed the efficiency of a Carnot cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] In mesoscopic heat engines, work per cycle of operation in general fluctuates due to thermal noise.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] If the cycle is performed quasi-statically, the fluctuations vanish even on the mesoscale.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] However, if the cycle is performed faster than the relaxation time of the working medium, the fluctuations of work are inevitable.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Nevertheless, when work and heat fluctuations are counted, an exact equality relates the exponential average of work performed by any heat engine to the heat transfer from the hotter heat bath.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Carnot realized that, in reality, it is not possible to build a thermodynamically reversible engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] So, real heat engines are even less efficient than indicated by Equation **3**.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] In addition, real engines that operate along the Carnot cycle style (isothermal expansion / adiabatic expansion / isothermal compression / adiabatic compression) are rare.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] Nevertheless, Equation **3** is extremely useful for determining the maximum efficiency that could ever be expected for a given set of thermal reservoirs.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The first prototype of the diesel engine was based on the principles of the Carnot cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] The Carnot heat engine is, ultimately, a theoretical construct based on an *idealized* thermodynamic system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] On a practical human-scale level the Carnot cycle has proven a valuable model, as in advancing the development of the diesel engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] However the requirement of perfect reversibility is unattainable in a practical sense, and, ultimately, a perfect Carnot engine is incapable of doing any work in a finite amount of time.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/carnot-cycle] As such, per Carnot's theorem, the Carnot engine may be thought as the theoretical limit of macroscopic scale heat engines rather than any practical device that could ever be built.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The **Diesel cycle** is a combustion process of a reciprocating internal combustion engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] In it, fuel is ignited by heat generated during the compression of air in the combustion chamber, into which fuel is then injected.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] This is in contrast to igniting the fuel-air mixture with a spark plug as in the Otto cycle (four-stroke/petrol) engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Diesel engines are used in aircraft, automobiles, power generation, diesel–electric locomotives, and both surface ships and submarines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The Diesel cycle is assumed to have constant pressure during the initial part of the combustion phase ( $V_{2}$ to $V_{3}$ in the diagram, below).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] This is an idealized mathematical model: real physical diesels do have an increase in pressure during this period, but it is less pronounced than in the Otto cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] In contrast, the idealized Otto cycle of a gasoline engine approximates a constant volume process during that phase.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The image shows a p–V diagram for the ideal Diesel cycle; where p is pressure and V the volume or v the specific volume if the process is placed on a unit mass basis.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The Diesel engine is a heat engine: it converts heat into work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] During the bottom isentropic processes (blue), energy is transferred into the system in the form of work $W_{in}$ , but by definition (isentropic) no energy is transferred into or out of the system in the form of heat.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] During the constant pressure (red, isobaric) process, energy enters the system as heat $Q_{in}$ .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] During the top isentropic processes (yellow), energy is transferred out of the system in the form of $W_{out}$ , but by definition (isentropic) no energy is transferred into or out of the system in the form of heat.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] During the constant volume (green, isochoric) process, some of the energy flows out of the system as heat through the right depressurizing process $Q_{out}$ .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The net work produced is also represented by the area enclosed by the cycle on the p–V diagram.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The net work is produced per cycle and is also called the useful work, as it can be turned to other useful types of energy and propel a vehicle (kinetic energy) or produce electrical energy.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The summation of many such cycles per unit of time is called the developed power.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The $W_{out}$ is also called the gross work, some of which is used in the next cycle of the engine to compress the next charge of air.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The maximum thermal efficiency of a Diesel cycle is dependent on the compression ratio and the cut-off ratio.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] $T_{3}$ can be approximated to the flame temperature of the fuel used.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The flame temperature can be approximated to the adiabatic flame temperature of the fuel with corresponding air-to-fuel ratio and compression pressure, $p_{3}$ . $T_{1}$ can be approximated to the inlet air temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] This formula only gives the ideal thermal efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The actual thermal efficiency will be significantly lower due to heat and friction losses.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The additional complexity for the Diesel formula comes around since the heat addition is at constant pressure and the heat rejection is at constant volume.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] The Otto cycle by comparison has both the heat addition and rejection at constant volume.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Comparing the two formulae it can be seen that for a given compression ratio (r), the *ideal* Otto cycle will be more efficient.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] However, a *real* diesel engine will be more efficient overall since it will have the ability to operate at higher compression ratios.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] If a petrol engine were to have the same compression ratio, then knocking (self-ignition) would occur and this would severely reduce the efficiency, whereas in a diesel engine, the self ignition is the desired behavior.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Additionally, both of these cycles are only idealizations, and the actual behavior does not divide as clearly or sharply.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Furthermore, the ideal Otto cycle formula stated above does not include throttling losses, which do not apply to diesel engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Diesel engines have the lowest specific fuel consumption of any large internal combustion engine employing a single cycle, 0.26 lb/hp·h (0.16 kg/kWh) for very large marine engines (combined cycle power plants are more efficient, but employ two engines rather than one).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Two-stroke diesels with high pressure forced induction, particularly turbocharging, make up a large percentage of the very largest diesel engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] In North America, diesel engines are primarily used in large trucks, where the low-stress, high-efficiency cycle leads to much longer engine life and lower operational costs.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] These advantages also make the diesel engine ideal for use in the heavy-haul railroad and earthmoving environments.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Many model airplanes use very simple "glow" and "diesel" engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] "Diesel" model airplane engines have variable compression ratios.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] Some 19th-century or earlier experimental engines used external flames, exposed by valves, for ignition, but this becomes less attractive with increasing compression.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] (It was the research of Nicolas Léonard Sadi Carnot that established the thermodynamic value of compression.) A historical implication of this is that the diesel engine could have been invented without the aid of electricity.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/diesel-cycle] See the development of the hot-bulb engine and indirect injection for historical significance.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A **heat engine** is a system that transfers thermal energy to do mechanical or electrical work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] While originally conceived in the context of mechanical energy, the concept of the heat engine has been applied to various other kinds of energy, particularly electrical, since at least the late 19th century.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The heat engine does this by bringing a working substance from a higher state temperature to a lower state temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A heat source supplies thermal energy that brings the working substance to the higher temperature state.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The working substance does work in the working body of the engine while transferring heat to the colder sink until it reaches a lower temperature state.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] During this process some of the thermal energy is converted into work by exploiting the properties of the working substance.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The working substance can be any system with a non-zero heat capacity, but it usually is a gas or liquid.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] During this process, some heat is normally lost to the surroundings and is not converted to work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Also, in a mechanical engine, some energy is unusable because of friction and drag.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In general, an engine is any machine that converts energy to mechanical work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Heat engines distinguish themselves from other types of engines by the fact that their efficiency is fundamentally limited by Carnot's theorem of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Since the heat source that supplies thermal energy to the engine can thus be powered by virtually any kind of energy, heat engines cover a wide range of applications.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Heat engines are often confused with the cycles they attempt to implement.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Typically, the term "engine" is used for a physical device and "cycle" for the models; thus, for example, a diesel engine is a machine which implements the Diesel cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In thermodynamics, heat engines are often modeled using a standard engineering model such as the Otto cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The theoretical model can be refined and augmented with actual data from an operating engine, using tools such as an indicator diagram.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Since very few actual implementations of heat engines exactly match their underlying thermodynamic cycles, one could say that a thermodynamic cycle is an ideal case of a mechanical engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In any case, fully understanding an engine and its efficiency requires a good understanding of the (possibly simplified or idealised) theoretical model, the practical nuances of an actual mechanical engine and the discrepancies between the two.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In general terms, the larger the difference in temperature between the hot source and the cold sink, the larger is the potential thermal efficiency of the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The maximum theoretical efficiency of a heat engine (which no engine ever attains) is equal to the temperature difference between the hot and cold ends divided by the temperature at the hot end, each expressed in absolute temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The efficiency of these processes is roughly proportional to the temperature drop across them.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Significant energy may be consumed by auxiliary equipment, such as pumps, which effectively reduces efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Although some cycles have a typical combustion location (internal or external), they can often be implemented with the other.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] For example, John Ericsson developed an external heated engine running on a cycle very much like the earlier Diesel cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In addition, externally heated engines can often be implemented in open or closed cycles.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Everyday examples of heat engines include the thermal power station, internal combustion engine, firearms, refrigerators and heat pumps.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Power stations are examples of heat engines run in a forward direction in which heat flows from a hot reservoir and flows into a cool reservoir to produce work as the desired product.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Refrigerators remove heat from within a thermally sealed chamber at low temperature and vent waste heat at a higher temperature to the environment and heat pumps take heat from the low temperature environment and 'vent' it into a thermally sealed chamber (a house) at higher temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In general heat engines exploit the thermal properties associated with the expansion and compression of gases according to the gas laws or the properties associated with phase changes between gas and liquid states.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Earth's atmosphere and hydrosphere—Earth's heat engine—are coupled processes that constantly even out solar heating imbalances through evaporation of surface water, convection, rainfall, winds and ocean circulation, when distributing heat around the globe.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A Hadley cell is an example of a heat engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] It involves the rising of warm and moist air in the earth's equatorial region and the descent of colder air in the subtropics creating a thermally driven direct circulation, with consequent net production of kinetic energy.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In phase change cycles and engines, the working fluids are gases and liquids.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The engine converts the working fluid from a gas to a liquid, from liquid to gas, or both, generating work from the fluid expansion or compression.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A domestic refrigerator is an example of a heat pump: a heat engine in reverse.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Work is used to create a heat differential.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Many cycles can run in reverse to move heat from the cold side to the hot side, making the cold side cooler and the hot side hotter.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Internal combustion engine versions of these cycles are, by their nature, not reversible.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The Barton evaporation engine is a heat engine based on a cycle producing power and cooled moist air from the evaporation of water into hot dry air.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Mesoscopic heat engines are nanoscale devices that may serve the goal of processing heat fluxes and perform useful work at small scales.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Potential applications include e.g. electric cooling devices.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In such mesoscopic heat engines, work per cycle of operation fluctuates due to thermal noise.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] There is exact equality that relates average of exponents of work performed by any heat engine and the heat transfer from the hotter heat bath.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] This relation transforms the Carnot's inequality into exact equality.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The efficiency of a heat engine relates how much useful work is output for a given amount of heat energy input.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In other words, a heat engine absorbs heat energy from the high temperature heat source, converting part of it to useful work and giving off the rest as waste heat to the cold temperature heat sink.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In general, the efficiency of a given heat transfer process is defined by the ratio of "what is taken out" to "what is put in".
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The efficiency is less than 100% because of the waste heat $Q_{c}<0$ unavoidably lost to the cold sink (and corresponding compression work put in) during the required recompression at the cold temperature before the power stroke of the engine can occur again.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The *theoretical* maximum efficiency of any heat engine depends only on the temperatures it operates between.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] This efficiency is usually derived using an ideal imaginary heat engine such as the Carnot heat engine, although other engines using different cycles can also attain maximum efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Note that $\Delta S_{h}$ is positive because isothermal expansion in the power stroke increases the multiplicity of the working fluid while $\Delta S_{c}$ is negative since recompression decreases the multiplicity.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] where $T_{h}$ is the absolute temperature of the hot source and $T_{c}$ that of the cold sink, usually measured in kelvins.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The reasoning behind this being the **maximal** efficiency goes as follows.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] It is first assumed that if a more efficient heat engine than a Carnot engine is possible, then it could be driven in reverse as a heat pump.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Mathematical analysis can be used to show that this assumed combination would result in a net decrease in entropy.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Since, by the second law of thermodynamics, this is statistically improbable to the point of exclusion, the Carnot efficiency is a theoretical upper bound on the reliable efficiency of *any* thermodynamic cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Empirically, no heat engine has ever been shown to run at a greater efficiency than a Carnot cycle heat engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Figure 2 and Figure 3 show variations on Carnot cycle efficiency with temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Figure 2 indicates how efficiency changes with an increase in the heat addition temperature for a constant compressor inlet temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Figure 3 indicates how the efficiency changes with an increase in the heat rejection temperature for a constant turbine inlet temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] By its nature, any maximally efficient Carnot cycle must operate at an infinitesimal temperature gradient; this is because any transfer of heat between two bodies of differing temperatures is irreversible, therefore the Carnot efficiency expression applies only to the infinitesimal limit.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The major problem is that the objective of most heat-engines is to output power, and infinitesimal power is seldom desired.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A different measure of ideal heat-engine efficiency is given by considerations of endoreversible thermodynamics, where the system is broken into reversible subsystems, but with non reversible interactions between them.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A classical example is the Curzon–Ahlborn engine, very similar to a Carnot engine, but where the thermal reservoirs at temperature $T_{h}$ and $T_{c}$ are allowed to be different from the temperatures of the substance going through the reversible Carnot cycle: $T'_{h}$ and $T'_{c}$ .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The heat transfers between the reservoirs and the substance are considered as conductive (and irreversible) in the form $dQ_{h,c}/dt=\alpha (T_{h,c}-T'_{h,c})$ .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] In this case, a tradeoff has to be made between power output and efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] If the engine is operated very slowly, the heat flux is low, $T\approx T'$ and the classical Carnot result is found $\eta =1-{\frac {T_{c}}{T_{h}}},$ but at the price of a vanishing power output.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] As shown, the Curzon–Ahlborn efficiency much more closely models that observed.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Heat engines have been known since antiquity but were only made into useful devices at the time of the industrial revolution in the 18th century.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Engineers have studied the various heat-engine cycles to improve the amount of usable work they could extract from a given power source.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Exploit the physical properties of the working fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The most common such exploitation is the use of water above the critical point (supercritical water).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A newer and very promising material for such applications is supercritical CO2.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] SO2 and xenon have also been considered for such applications.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Downsides include issues of corrosion and erosion, the different chemical behavior above and below the critical point, the needed high pressures and – in the case of sulfur dioxide and to a lesser extent carbon dioxide – toxicity.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Among the mentioned compounds xenon is least suitable for use in a nuclear reactor due to the high neutron absorption cross section of almost all isotopes of xenon, whereas carbon dioxide and water can also double as a neutron moderator for a thermal spectrum reactor.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Exploit the chemical properties of the working fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] A fairly new and novel exploit is to use exotic working fluids with advantageous chemical properties.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] One such is nitrogen dioxide (NO2), a toxic component of smog, which has a natural dimer as di-nitrogen tetraoxide (N2O4).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] At low temperature, the N2O4 is compressed and then heated.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] The increasing temperature causes each N2O4 to break apart into two NO2 molecules.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] This lowers the molecular weight of the working fluid, which drastically increases the efficiency of the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Once the NO2 has expanded through the turbine, it is cooled by the heat sink, which makes it recombine into N2O4.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] This is then fed back by the compressor for another cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] Such species as aluminium bromide (Al2Br6), NOCl, and Ga2I6 have all been investigated for such uses.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/heat-engine] To date, their drawbacks have not warranted their use, despite the efficiency gains that can be realized.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] An **Otto cycle** (named after Nicolaus Otto) is an idealized thermodynamic cycle that describes the functioning of a typical spark ignition piston engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] It is the thermodynamic cycle most commonly found in automobile engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The Otto cycle is a description of what happens to a gas as it is subjected to changes of pressure, temperature, volume, addition of heat, and removal of heat.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The gas that is subjected to those changes is called the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The system, in this case, is defined to be the fluid (gas) within the cylinder.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Conversely, by describing the changes that take place within the system it also describes the system's effect on the environment.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The purpose of the Otto cycle is to study the production of net work from the system that can propel a vehicle and its occupants in the environment.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The isentropic process of compression or expansion implies that there will be no inefficiency (loss of mechanical energy), and there be no transfer of heat into or out of the system during that process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The cylinder and piston are assumed to be impermeable to heat during that time.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Work is performed on the system during the lower isentropic compression process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Heat flows into the Otto cycle through the left pressurizing process and some of it flows back out through the right depressurizing process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The summation of the work added to the system plus the heat added minus the heat removed yields the net mechanical work generated by the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The Otto cycle consists of isentropic compression, heat addition at constant volume, isentropic expansion, and rejection of heat at constant volume.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The four-stroke engine was first patented by Alphonse Beau de Rochas in 1861.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Before, in about 1854–1857, two Italians (Eugenio Barsanti and Felice Matteucci) invented an engine that was rumored to be very similar, but the patent was lost.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The first person to build a working four-stroke engine, a stationary engine using a coal gas – air mixture for fuel (a gas engine) was German engineer Nicolaus Otto.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] This is why the four-stroke principle today is commonly known as the Otto cycle and four-stroke engines using spark plugs often are called Otto engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] As the piston is capable of moving along the cylinder, the volume of the gas changes with its position in the cylinder.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The compression and expansion processes induced on the gas by the movement of the piston are idealized as reversible, i.e., no useful work is lost through turbulence or friction and no heat is transferred to or from the gas during those two processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] After the expansion is completed in the cylinder, the remaining heat is extracted and finally the gas is exhausted to the environment.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Mechanical work is produced during the expansion process and some of that used to compress the air mass of the next cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The mechanical work produced minus that used for the compression process is the net work gained and that can be used for propulsion or for driving other machines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Alternatively the net work gained is the difference between the heat produced and the heat removed.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] A mass of air (working fluid) is drawn into the cylinder, from 0 to 1, at atmospheric pressure (constant pressure) through the open intake valve, while the exhaust valve is closed during this process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Piston moves from crank end (BDC, bottom dead centre and maximum volume) to cylinder head end (*TDC*, top dead centre and minimum volume) as the working gas with initial state 1 is compressed isentropically to state point 2, through compression ratio (*V*1/*V*2).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Mechanically this is the isentropic compression of the air/fuel mixture in the cylinder, also known as the compression stroke.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] This isentropic process assumes that no mechanical energy is lost due to friction and no heat is transferred to or from the gas, hence the process is reversible.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The compression process requires that mechanical work be added to the working gas.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Generally the compression ratio is around 9–10:1 (*V*1:*V*2) for a typical engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The piston is momentarily at rest at *TDC*.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] During this instant, which is known as the ignition phase, the air/fuel mixture remains in a small volume at the top of the compression stroke.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Heat is added to the working fluid by the combustion of the injected fuel, with the volume essentially being held constant.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The pressure rises and the ratio $(P_{3}/P_{2})$ is called the "explosion ratio".
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The increased high pressure exerts a force on the piston and pushes it towards the *BDC*.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Expansion of working fluid takes place isentropically and work is done by the system on the piston.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The volume ratio $V_{4}/V_{3}$ is called the "isentropic expansion ratio".
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] (For the Otto cycle is the same as the compression ratio $V_{1}/V_{2}$ ).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Mechanically this is the expansion of the hot gaseous mixture in the cylinder known as expansion (power) stroke.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The piston is momentarily at rest at *BDC*.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The working gas pressure drops instantaneously from point 4 to point 1 during a constant volume process as heat is removed to an idealized external sink that is brought into contact with the cylinder head.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] In modern internal combustion engines, the heat-sink may be surrounding air (for low powered engines), or a circulating fluid, such as coolant.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] As the piston moves from "BDC" (point 1) to "TDC" (point 0) with the exhaust valve opened, the gaseous mixture is vented to the atmosphere and the process starts anew.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] In this process 1–2 the piston does work on the gas and in process 3–4 the gas does work on the piston during those isentropic compression and expansion processes, respectively.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Processes 2–3 and 4–1 are isochoric processes; heat is transferred into the system from 2—3 and out of the system from 4–1 but no work is done on the system or extracted from the system during those processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] No work is done during an isochoric (constant volume) process because addition or removal of work from a system requires the movement of the boundaries of the system; hence, as the cylinder volume does not change, no shaft work is added to or removed from the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Four different equations are used to describe those four processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] During a complete cycle, the gas returns to its original state of temperature, pressure and volume, hence the net internal energy change of the system (gas) is zero.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] As a result, the energy (heat or work) added to the system must be offset by energy (heat or work) that leaves the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] In the analysis of thermodynamic systems, the convention is to account energy that enters the system as positive and energy that leaves the system is accounted as negative.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The above states that the system (the mass of gas) returns to the original thermodynamic state it was in at the start of the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Where $E_{\text{in}}$ is energy added to the system from 1–2–3 and $E_{\text{out}}$ is energy removed from the system from 3–4–1.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] To illustrate the example we choose some values to the points in the illustration: ${\begin{aligned}U_{1}&=1\\U_{2}&=5\\U_{3}&=9\\U_{4}&=4\end{aligned}}$ These values are arbitrarily but rationally selected.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The work and heat terms can then be calculated.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Note that energy added to the system is counted as positive and energy leaving the system is counted as negative and the summation is zero as expected for a complete cycle that returns the system to its original state.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The net energy out of the system as work is -1, meaning the system has produced one net unit of energy that leaves the system in the form of work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] As energy added to the system as heat is positive.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] From the above it appears as if the system gained one unit of heat.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] This matches the energy produced by the system as work out of the system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Thermal efficiency is the quotient of the net work from the system, to the heat added to system.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Alternatively, thermal efficiency can be derived by strictly heat added and heat rejected.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] In the Otto cycle, there is no heat transfer during the process 1–2 and 3–4 as they are isentropic processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Heat is supplied only during the constant volume processes 2–3 and heat is rejected only during the constant volume processes 4–1.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The above values are absolute values that might, for instance , have units of joules (assuming the MKS system of units are to be used) and would be of use for a particular engine with particular dimensions.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] In the study of thermodynamic systems the extensive quantities such as energy, volume, or entropy (versus intensive quantities of temperature and pressure) are placed on a unit mass basis, and so too are the calculations, making those more general and therefore of more general use.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Hence, each term involving an extensive quantity could be divided by the mass, giving the terms units of joules/kg (specific energy), meters3/kg (specific volume), or joules/(kelvin·kg) (specific entropy, heat capacity) etc. and would be represented using lower case letters, u, v, s, etc.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Equation 1 can now be related to the specific heat equation for constant volume.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The specific heats are particularly useful for thermodynamic calculations involving the ideal gas model.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Inserting the specific heat equation into the thermal efficiency equation (Equation 2) yields.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Next, noting from the diagrams $T_{4}/T_{1}=T_{3}/T_{2}$ (see isentropic relations for an ideal gas), thus both of these can be omitted.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Since the Otto cycle uses isentropic processes during the compression (process 1 to 2) and expansion (process 3 to 4) the isentropic equations of ideal gases and the constant pressure/volume relations can be used to yield Equations 3 & 4.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] From analyzing equation 6 it is evident that the Otto cycle efficiency depends directly upon the compression ratio r .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Since the $\gamma$ for air is 1.4, an increase in r will produce an increase in $\eta$ .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] However, the $\gamma$ for combustion products of the fuel/air mixture is often taken at approximately 1.3.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The foregoing discussion implies that it is more efficient to have a high compression ratio.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The standard ratio is approximately 10:1 for typical automobiles.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Usually this does not increase much because of the possibility of autoignition, or "knock", which places an upper limit on the compression ratio.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] During the compression process 1–2 the temperature rises, therefore an increase in the compression ratio causes an increase in temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Autoignition occurs when the temperature of the fuel/air mixture becomes too high before it is ignited by the flame front.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The compression stroke is intended to compress the products before the flame ignites the mixture.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] If the compression ratio is increased, the mixture may auto-ignite before the compression stroke is complete, leading to "engine knocking".
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] This can damage engine components and will decrease the brake horsepower of the engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The power produced by the Otto cycle is an energy developed per unit of time.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The Otto engines are called four-stroke engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The intake stroke and compression stroke require one rotation of the engine crankshaft.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The power stroke and exhaust stroke require another rotation.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] For two rotations there is one work generating stroke..
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] (again, using the sign convention, the minus sign implies energy is leaving the system as work).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] If the units used were MKS the cycle would have produced one joule of energy in the form of work.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] For an engine of a particular displacement, such as one liter, the mass of gas of the system can be calculated assuming the engine is operating at standard temperature (20 °C) and pressure (1 atm).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] At an engine speed of 3000 RPM there are 1500 work-strokes/minute or 25 work-strokes/second.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] If the engine uses multiple cylinders with the same displacement, the result would be multiplied by the number of cylinders.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] These results are the product of the values of the internal energy that were assumed for the four states of the system at the end each of the four strokes (two rotations).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] They were selected only for the sake of illustration, and are obviously of low value.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Substitution of actual values from an actual engine would produce results closer to that of the engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Whose results would be higher than the actual engine as there are many simplifying assumptions made in the analysis that overlook inefficiencies.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Such results would overestimate the power output.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The difference between the exhaust and intake pressures and temperatures means that some increase in efficiency can be gained by use of a turbocharger, removing from the exhaust flow some part of the remaining energy and transferring that to the intake flow to increase the intake pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] A gas turbine can extract useful work energy from the exhaust stream and that can then be used to pressurize the intake air.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The pressure and temperature of the exhausting gases would be reduced as they expand through the gas turbine and that work is then applied to the intake gas stream, increasing its pressure and temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The transfer of energy amounts to an efficiency improvement and the resulting power density of the engine is also improved.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] The intake air is typically cooled so as to reduce its volume as the work produced per stroke is a direct function of the amount of mass taken into the cylinder; denser air will produce more work per cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Practically speaking the intake air mass temperature must also be reduced to prevent premature ignition in a petrol fueled engine; hence, an intercooler is used to remove some energy as heat and so reduce the intake temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/otto-cycle] Such a scheme both increases the engine's efficiency and power.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The **Rankine cycle** is an idealized thermodynamic cycle describing the process by which certain heat engines, such as steam turbines or reciprocating steam engines, allow mechanical work to be extracted from a fluid as it moves between a heat source and heat sink.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The Rankine cycle is named after William John Macquorn Rankine, a Scottish polymath professor at Glasgow University.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Heat energy is supplied to the system via a boiler where the working fluid (typically water) is converted to a high-pressure gaseous state (steam) in order to turn a turbine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] After passing over the turbine the fluid is allowed to condense back into a liquid state as waste heat energy is rejected before being returned to the boiler, completing the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Friction losses throughout the system are often neglected for the purpose of simplifying calculations as such losses are usually much less significant than thermodynamic losses, especially in larger systems.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The Rankine cycle closely describes the process by which steam engines commonly found in thermal power generation plants harness the thermal energy of a fuel or other heat source to generate electricity.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Possible heat sources include combustion of fossil fuels such as coal, natural gas, and oil, use of mined resources for nuclear fission, renewable fuels like biomass and ethanol, and energy capture of natural sources such as concentrated solar power and geothermal energy.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Common heat sinks include ambient air above or around a facility and bodies of water such as rivers, ponds, and oceans.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The ability of a Rankine engine to harness energy depends on the relative temperature difference between the heat source and heat sink.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The greater the differential, the more mechanical power can be efficiently extracted out of heat energy, as per Carnot's theorem.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The efficiency of the Rankine cycle is limited by the high heat of vaporization of the working fluid.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Unless the pressure and temperature reach supercritical levels in the boiler, the temperature range over which the cycle can operate is quite small.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] As of 2022, most supercritical power plants adopt a steam inlet pressure of 24.1 MPa and inlet temperature between 538 °C and 566 °C, which results in plant efficiency of 40%.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] However, if pressure is further increased to 31 MPa the power plant is referred to as ultra-supercritical, and one can increase the steam inlet temperature to 600 °C, thus achieving a thermal efficiency of 42%.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] This low steam turbine entry temperature (compared to a gas turbine) is why the Rankine (steam) cycle is often used as a bottoming cycle to recover otherwise rejected heat in combined-cycle gas turbine power stations.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Rankine engines generally operate in a closed loop in which the working fluid is reused.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The water vapor with condensed droplets often seen billowing from power stations is created by the cooling systems (not directly from the closed-loop Rankine power cycle).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] This "exhaust" heat is represented by the "Qout" flowing out of the lower side of the cycle shown in the T–s diagram below.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Cooling towers operate as large heat exchangers by absorbing the latent heat of vaporization of the working fluid and simultaneously evaporating cooling water to the atmosphere.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] While many substances can be used as the working fluid, water is usually chosen for its simple chemistry, relative abundance, low cost, and thermodynamic properties.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] By condensing the working steam vapor to a liquid, the pressure at the turbine outlet is lowered, and the energy required by the feed pump consumes only 1% to 3% of the turbine output power.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] These factors contribute to a higher efficiency for the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The benefit of this is offset by the low temperatures of steam admitted to the turbine(s).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Gas turbines, for instance, have turbine entry temperatures approaching 1500 °C.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] However, the thermal efficiencies of actual large steam power stations and large modern gas turbine stations are similar.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] There are four processes in the Rankine cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The states are identified by numbers (in brown) in the T–s diagram.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] In an ideal Rankine cycle the pump and turbine would be isentropic: i.e., the pump and turbine would generate no entropy and would hence maximize the net work output.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Processes 1–2 and 3–4 would be represented by vertical lines on the T–s diagram and more closely resemble that of the Carnot cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The Rankine cycle shown here prevents the state of the working fluid from ending up in the superheated vapor region after the expansion in the turbine, [1] which reduces the energy removed by the condensers.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] $\eta _{\text{therm}}$ defines the thermodynamic efficiency of the cycle as the ratio of net power output to heat input.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Each of the next four equations[1] is derived from the energy and mass balance for a control volume.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] In a real power-plant cycle (the name "Rankine" cycle is used only for the ideal cycle), the compression by the pump and the expansion in the turbine are not isentropic.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] In other words, these processes are non-reversible, and entropy is increased during the two processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] This somewhat increases the power required by the pump and decreases the power generated by the turbine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] In particular, the efficiency of the steam turbine will be limited by water-droplet formation.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] As the water condenses, water droplets hit the turbine blades at high speed, causing pitting and erosion, gradually decreasing the life of turbine blades and efficiency of the turbine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The easiest way to overcome this problem is by superheating the steam.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] On the T–s diagram above, state 3 is at a border of the two-phase region of steam and water, so after expansion the steam will be very wet.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] By superheating, state 3 will move to the right (and up) in the diagram and hence produce a drier steam after expansion.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Increasing the temperature of the steam into the superheat region is a simple way of doing this.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] There are also variations of the basic Rankine cycle designed to raise the thermal efficiency of the cycle in this way; two of these are described below.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The purpose of a reheating cycle is to remove the moisture carried by the steam at the final stages of the expansion process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] In this variation, two turbines work in series.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The first accepts vapor from the boiler at high pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] After the vapor has passed through the first turbine, it re-enters the boiler and is reheated before passing through a second, lower-pressure, turbine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The reheat temperatures are very close or equal to the inlet temperatures, whereas the optimal reheat pressure needed is only one fourth of the original boiler pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Among other advantages, this prevents the vapor from condensing during its expansion and thereby reducing the damage in the turbine blades, and improves the efficiency of the cycle, because more of the heat flow into the cycle occurs at higher temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The reheat cycle was first introduced in the 1920s, but was not operational for long due to technical difficulties.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] In the 1940s, it was reintroduced with the increasing manufacture of high-pressure boilers, and eventually double reheating was introduced in the 1950s, with the idea behind double reheating is to increase the average temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] It was observed that more than two stages of reheating are generally unnecessary, since the next stage increases the cycle efficiency only half as much as the preceding stage.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Today, double reheating is commonly used in power plants that operate under supercritical pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The regenerative Rankine cycle is so named because after emerging from the condenser (possibly as a subcooled liquid) the working fluid is heated by steam tapped from the hot portion of the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] On the diagram shown, the fluid at 2 is mixed with the fluid at 4 (both at the same pressure) to end up with the saturated liquid at 7.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] This is called "direct-contact heating".
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The Regenerative Rankine cycle (with minor variants) is commonly used in real power stations.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Another variation sends *bleed steam* from between turbine stages to feedwater heaters to preheat the water on its way from the condenser to the boiler.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] These heaters do not mix the input steam and condensate, function as an ordinary tubular heat exchanger, and are named "closed feedwater heaters".
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Regeneration increases the cycle heat input temperature by eliminating the addition of heat from the boiler/fuel source at the relatively low feedwater temperatures that would exist without regenerative feedwater heating.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] This improves the efficiency of the cycle, as more of the heat flow into the cycle occurs at higher temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The organic Rankine cycle (ORC) uses an organic fluid such as n-pentane or toluene in place of water and steam.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] This allows use of lower-temperature heat sources, such as solar ponds, which typically operate at around 70 –90 °C.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The efficiency of the cycle is much lower as a result of the lower temperature range, but this can be worthwhile because of the lower cost involved in gathering heat at this lower temperature.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] Alternatively, fluids can be used that have boiling points above water, and this may have thermodynamic benefits (See, for example, mercury vapour turbine).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The properties of the actual working fluid have great influence on the quality of steam (vapour) after the expansion step, influencing the design of the whole cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The Rankine cycle does not restrict the working fluid in its definition, so the name "organic cycle" is simply a marketing concept and the cycle should not be regarded as a separate thermodynamic cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] The Rankine cycle applied using a supercritical fluid combines the concepts of heat regeneration and supercritical Rankine cycle into a unified process called the regenerative supercritical cycle (RGSC).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/rankine-cycle] It is optimised for temperature sources 125–450 °C.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] A **thermodynamic cycle** consists of linked sequences of thermodynamic processes that involve transfer of heat and work into and out of the system, while varying pressure, temperature, and other state variables within the system, and that eventually returns the system to its initial state.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] In the process of passing through a cycle, the working fluid (system) may convert heat from a warm source into useful work, and dispose of the remaining heat to a cold sink, thereby acting as a heat engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Conversely, the cycle may be reversed and use work to move heat from a cold source and transfer it to a warm sink thereby acting as a heat pump.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] If at every point in the cycle the system is in thermodynamic equilibrium, the cycle is reversible.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Whether carried out reversibly or irreversibly, the net entropy change of the system is zero, as entropy is a state function.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] During a closed cycle, the system returns to its original thermodynamic state of temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Process quantities (or path quantities), such as heat and work are process dependent.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The above states that there is no change of the internal energy ( U ) of the system over the cycle. $E_{in}$ represents the total work and heat input during the cycle and $E_{out}$ would be the total work and heat output during the cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The repeating nature of the process path allows for continuous operation, making the cycle an important concept in thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Thermodynamic cycles are often represented mathematically as quasistatic processes in the modeling of the workings of an actual device.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Two primary classes of thermodynamic cycles are **power cycles** and **heat pump cycles**.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Power cycles are cycles which convert some heat input into a mechanical work output, while heat pump cycles transfer heat from low to high temperatures by using mechanical work as the input.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Cycles composed entirely of quasistatic processes can operate as power or heat pump cycles by controlling the process direction.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] On a pressure–volume (PV) diagram or temperature–entropy diagram, the clockwise and counterclockwise directions indicate power and heat pump cycles, respectively.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Because the net variation in state properties during a thermodynamic cycle is zero, it forms a closed loop on a *P-V* diagram.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] A *P-V* diagram is often labelled with pressure (*P*) on the y-axis and volume (*V*) on the x-axis.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Equation (2) is consistent with the First Law; even though the internal energy changes during the course of the cyclic process, when the cyclic process finishes the system's internal energy is the same as the energy it had when the process began.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] If the cyclic process moves clockwise around the loop, then $W_{net}$ will be positive, the cyclic machine will transform part of the heat exchanged into work and it represents a heat engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] If it moves counterclockwise, then $W_{net}$ will be negative, the cyclic machine will require work to absorb heat at a low temperature and reject it at a higher temperature and it represents a heat pump.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The Otto Cycle is an example of a reversible thermodynamic cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Thermodynamic power cycles are the basis for the operation of heat engines, which supply most of the world's electric power and run the vast majority of motor vehicles.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Power cycles can be organized into two categories: real cycles and ideal cycles.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Cycles encountered in real world devices (real cycles) are difficult to analyze because of the presence of complicating effects (friction), and the absence of sufficient time for the establishment of equilibrium conditions.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] For the purpose of analysis and design, idealized models (ideal cycles) are created; these ideal models allow engineers to study the effects of major parameters that dominate the cycle without having to spend significant time working out intricate details present in the real cycle model.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Power cycles can also be divided according to the type of heat engine they seek to model.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The most common cycles used to model internal combustion engines are the Otto cycle, which models gasoline engines, and the Diesel cycle, which models diesel engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Cycles that model external combustion engines include the Brayton cycle, which models gas turbines, the Rankine cycle, which models steam turbines, the Stirling cycle, which models hot air engines, and the Ericsson cycle, which also models hot air engines.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Thermodynamic heat pump cycles are the models for household heat pumps and refrigerators.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] There is no difference between the two except the purpose of the refrigerator is to cool a very small space while the household heat pump is intended to warm or cool a house.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Both work by moving heat from a cold space to a warm space.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The most common refrigeration cycle is the vapor compression cycle, which models systems using refrigerants that change phase.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The absorption refrigeration cycle is an alternative that absorbs the refrigerant in a liquid solution rather than evaporating it.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Gas refrigeration cycles include the reversed Brayton cycle and the Hampson–Linde cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Multiple compression and expansion cycles allow gas refrigeration systems to liquify gases.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Thermodynamic cycles may be used to model real devices and systems, typically by making a series of assumptions to reduce the problem to a more manageable form.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] For example, as shown in the figure, devices such a gas turbine or jet engine can be modeled as a Brayton cycle.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The actual device is made up of a series of stages, each of which is itself modeled as an idealized thermodynamic process.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Although each stage which acts on the working fluid is a complex real device, they may be modelled as idealized processes which approximate their real behavior.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] If energy is added by means other than combustion, then a further assumption is that the exhaust gases would be passed from the exhaust to a heat exchanger that would sink the waste heat to the environment and the working gas would be reused at the inlet stage.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The difference between an idealized cycle and actual performance may be significant.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] As the net work output for a cycle is represented by the interior of the cycle, there is a significant difference between the predicted work output of the ideal cycle and the actual work output shown by a real engine.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] It may also be observed that the real individual processes diverge from their idealized counterparts; e.g., isochoric expansion (process 1-2) occurs with some actual volume change.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] In practice, simple idealized thermodynamic cycles are usually made out of four thermodynamic processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Any thermodynamic processes may be used.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] If the working substance is a perfect gas, U is only a function of T for a closed system since its internal pressure vanishes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Assuming that $C_{v}$ is constant, $\Delta U=C_{v}\Delta T$ for any process undergone by a perfect gas.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Under this set of assumptions, for processes A and C we have $W=p\Delta v$ and $Q=C_{p}\Delta T$ , whereas for processes B and D we have $W=0$ and $Q=\Delta U=C_{v}\Delta T$ .
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] If the total heat flow per cycle is required, this is easily obtained.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Thus, the total heat flow per cycle is calculated without knowing the heat capacities and temperature changes for each step (although this information would be needed to assess the thermodynamic efficiency of the cycle).
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The Carnot cycle is a cycle composed of the totally reversible processes of isentropic compression and expansion and isothermal heat addition and rejection.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] where ${T_{L}}$ is the lowest cycle temperature and ${T_{H}}$ the highest.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The second law of thermodynamics limits the efficiency and COP for all cyclic devices to levels at or below the Carnot efficiency.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] The Stirling cycle and Ericsson cycle are two other reversible cycles that use regeneration to obtain isothermal heat transfer.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] A Stirling cycle is like an Otto cycle, except that the adiabats are replaced by isotherms.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] It is also the same as an Ericsson cycle with the isobaric processes substituted for constant volume processes.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] Heat flows into the loop through the top isotherm and the left isochore, and some of this heat flows back out through the bottom isotherm and the right isochore, but most of the heat flow is through the pair of isotherms.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] This makes sense since all the work done by the cycle is done by the pair of isothermal processes, which are described by *Q=W*.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] This suggests that all the net heat comes in through the top isotherm.
[src:thermodynamic-cycles/thermodynamic-cycle] meaning that the net entropy change of the working fluid over a cycle is zero.
